Part I - Prosper loan data Analysis¶

by Ben Mumo¶

Introduction¶

This is a financial dataset that contains 113,937 loans with 81 variables on each loan, including loan amount, borrower rate (or interest rate), current loan status, borrower income, and many others.

In [10]:
#replace the missing values in ProsperScore with its median
df["ProsperScore"].fillna(df["ProsperScore"].median(), inplace=True)
In [11]:
#replace the missing values in EmploymentStatusDuration with its median
df['EmploymentStatusDuration'].fillna(df['EmploymentStatusDuration'].median(), inplace=True)

According to Bank of America Borrower APR is APR is the annual cost of a loan to a borrower — including fees.

Therefore we will get the median difference between BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR and add that value to the Borrower rate of our missing APR

In [12]:
#get the median difference
borrowerfee = df['BorrowerAPR'].median() - df['BorrowerRate'].median()
In [13]:
#replace the missing values with the new value
df['BorrowerAPR'].fillna(df['BorrowerRate']+borrowerfee, inplace=True)
df['BorrowerAPR'].isna().sum()
Out[13]:
0
In [14]:
median_losses = df['BorrowerRate'].median()- df['EstimatedEffectiveYield'].median()
df['EstimatedEffectiveYield'].fillna(df['BorrowerRate'] - median_losses, inplace=True)

df['EstimatedEffectiveYield'].isna().sum()

According to Investopedia The effective yield is the true interest rate on an investment or loan because it takes into account the effects of compounding.

These effects of compounding include losses incurred from interest charge-offs and fees. (We get the losses by calculating the difference between Borrower rate and Effective Yield.) We will therefore get the median of these losses and remove it from the Borrower rate, then replace the missing values in Effective Yield with our new value

New Variable¶

One of the biggest use cases of banking data is to check if the loan will be paid or defaulted. So I engineered a feature called Loan_Default with 0 to mean the loan is fully paid and 1 to mean the loan was either defaulted or charged off.

To make this approach easier, we will drop all "current" loan status since we don't know if they will complete or default, then all "past due","charged-off" and "cancellation", will be classified as defaults.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 113937 rows and 81 coumns in the dataset. It has different data types, int, float,bool and object.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The very basic info I look out for in loan datasets, is loan defaulters, hence I engineered a feature called "Loan_default", from the "Loan Status" feature to distinct two categories, if the person is a loan defaulter or not. This will help me further my case study into building a prediction model for loan defaulters

The other feature of interest is the Estimated Effective yield which is basically the interest rate charged on the loans. I chose this feature over Borrower Rate, because According to Investopedia The effective yield is the true interest rate on an investment or loan.I therefore want to see how the rest of the features afect the effective yield.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

In support of investigating Estimated Effective Yield, features like ProsperScore, LoanOriginalAmount, MonthlyLoanPayment and Term might affect the feature negatively or positively.

Univariate Exploration¶

In this section, I investigate distributions of individual variables and take note of unusual data points.

Estimated Effective Yield¶

EstimatedEffectiveYield is the Yield of lenders from borrowers minus the processing fee and late fines

In [21]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8,5])
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
bins = np.arange(0, df.BorrowerAPR.max()+0.05,0.01)
plt.hist(data=df, x='EstimatedEffectiveYield', bins = bins,color=base_color);
plt.xlabel('EstimatedEffectiveYield');
plt.title('Distribution of Estimated Effective Yield');

The distribution of Estimated Effective Yield is multimodial, with several peaks. Clearly very few to no loans have a effective yield past 0.35

Prosper Score¶

Prosper score is a custom risk store built using historical prosper data. It ranges from 1-10 10 being the least risky

In [22]:
plt.figure(figsize=[8,5])
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.countplot(data=df, x='ProsperScore', color=base_color);

Most of the borrowers are scored at 6, with very few of the borrowers at the extreme ends of the scores, that is 1 and 11

There is a positive correlation between Monthly loan payment and loan original amount, the correlation coefficient is 0.932. There is however a negative correlation between loan amount and effective yield, the correlation coefficient is -0.267

ProsperScore VS EstimatedEffectiveYield¶

In [30]:
plt.figure(figsize=[12,5])
base_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
sb.violinplot(data = df, y='EstimatedEffectiveYield',x='ProsperScore', color=base_color);
plt.title('Effect of Prosper Score on Estimated Effective Yield');

A higher Prosper score depicts a better borrower and a lower prosper score depicts a not-so-good borrower. From the plot we notice how the white dot, which is the median of estimated effective yield, drops as the Prosper score increases. This means lenders allow better interest rates to borrowers with higher rating. I best believe this acts as an incentive to keep them.

As we can see the longer the term, the higher the interest rate, however the difference in increase is not as big, this is obviously encouraging for borrowers, since they would run away from big loans due to very high interest rates

The regplot shows that as the Loan amount increases, the Effective yield decreases, however it is important to note the difference is slight and not as drastic.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

The prosper score has a big impact on the effective yield, since better scores are granted the lesser effective yield amounts than poorer scores. I also noticed that as the Loan amount increases, the effective yield decreases, which is a good incentive for people to borrow bigger amounts.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

It was kinda obvious that bigger loan amounts come with longer loan terms. It was also evident that there is a positive correlation between Monthly loan payment and Loan Amount.

Effect of Prosper Score on the relationship between loan amount and effective yield¶

In [38]:
g=sb.FacetGrid(data=df, aspect=1.2,col='ProsperScore', col_wrap=4)
g.map(sb.regplot, 'LoanOriginalAmount', 'EstimatedEffectiveYield', x_jitter=0.04, scatter_kws={'alpha':0.01});
g.add_legend();

It is clear that better prosper score decreases the effective yield but increases the Loan amount. Lesser score have higher effective yield and lesser loan amounts.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

I looked into the effect of Prosper score and term on effective yield. The exploration showed that better scores decrease the effective yield and increases the loan amount and vice versa

I also looked into the effect of Prosper Score and term on Loan amount. I observed that higher scores were associated with longer loan terms and bigger loan amounts. Prosper Score and Loan terms strengthened each other in looking into Original Loan amount and Estimated Effective Yield.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It was interesting that the relationship between effective yield and loan amount was negative as opposed to what I always believed, that is, bigger loans attract higher effective yields.
